element.name: CtlNotSignatureValid
element.short: Specifies that the certificate trust list (CTL) contains an invalid signature.

element.name: CtlNotTimeValid
element.short: Specifies that the certificate trust list (CTL) is not valid because of an invalid time value, such as one that indicates that the CTL has expired.

element.name: CtlNotValidForUsage
element.short: Specifies that the certificate trust list (CTL) is not valid for this use.

element.name: Cyclic
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain could not be built.

element.name: ExplicitDistrust
element.short: Specifies that the certificate is explicitly distrusted.

element.name: HasExcludedNameConstraint
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid because a certificate has excluded a name constraint.

element.name: HasNotDefinedNameConstraint
element.short: Specifies that the certificate has an undefined name constraint.

element.name: HasNotPermittedNameConstraint
element.short: Specifies that the certificate has an impermissible name constraint.

element.name: HasNotSupportedCriticalExtension
element.short: Specifies that the certificate does not support a critical extension.

element.name: HasNotSupportedNameConstraint
element.short: Specifies that the certificate does not have a supported name constraint or has a name constraint that is unsupported.

element.name: HasWeakSignature
element.short: Specifies that the certificate has not been strong signed. Typically, this indicates that the MD2 or MD5 hashing algorithms were used to create a hash of the certificate.

element.name: InvalidBasicConstraints
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to invalid basic constraints.

element.name: InvalidExtension
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to an invalid extension.

element.name: InvalidNameConstraints
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to invalid name constraints.

element.name: InvalidPolicyConstraints
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to invalid policy constraints.

element.name: NoError
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain has no errors.

element.name: NoIssuanceChainPolicy
element.short: Specifies that there is no certificate policy extension in the certificate. This error would occur if a group policy has specified that all certificates must have a certificate policy.

element.name: NotSignatureValid
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to an invalid certificate signature.

element.name: NotTimeNested
element.short: Deprecated. Specifies that the CA (certificate authority) certificate and the issued certificate have validity periods that are not nested. For example, the CA cert can be valid from January 1 to December 1 and the issued certificate from January 2 to December 2, which would mean the validity periods are not nested.

element.name: NotTimeValid
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is not valid due to an invalid time value, such as a value that indicates an expired certificate.

element.name: NotValidForUsage
element.short: Specifies that the key usage is not valid.

element.name: OfflineRevocation
element.short: Specifies that the online certificate revocation list (CRL) the X509 chain relies on is currently offline.

element.name: PartialChain
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain could not be built up to the root certificate.

element.name: RevocationStatusUnknown
element.short: Specifies that it is not possible to determine whether the certificate has been revoked. This can be due to the certificate revocation list (CRL) being offline or unavailable.

element.name: Revoked
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to a revoked certificate.

element.name: UntrustedRoot
element.short: Specifies that the X509 chain is invalid due to an untrusted root certificate.
